               <msContents>
                  <summary>The undated sixth volume of a complete set of the <title>Rawz̤at al-Ṣafā</title> (Garden of Purity), a general history from the creation of the world to the time of the author, together
                     with <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_14603"
                        ><idno>Persian MS 387</idno></ref>, <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_14604"
                           >388</ref>, <ref
                              target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_14605">389</ref>, <ref
                                 target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6887">390</ref>, 
                     <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6888">391</ref>, <ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6890">393</ref>, and <ref
                              target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6891">394</ref>. While uniformly bound, the variant dimensions, formats and colophons within the set suggest that former owner George William Hamilton (1807–1868) assembled it together from disparate volumes completed in various locations and at different times; however, this specific manuscript comports with 
                     <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6890"><idno>Persian MS 393</idno></ref>
                  </summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_392-item1">
                     <author key="person_175393012" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/175393012/" change="#ids-cleanup">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">Mīr Khvānd, Muḥammad ibn Khāvandshāh, 1433-1498</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa">مير خواند، محمد بن خواندشاه</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_273" change="#ids-cleanup">Rawz̤at al-ṣafā fī Sīrat al-anbiyā wa-al-Mulūk</title>
                     <title xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" type="alt" key="work_273" change="#ids-cleanup">Rawḍat al-ṣafāʼ</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_273" change="#ids-cleanup">روضة الصفاء فی سیرة الانبيا و الملوك</title>
                                        <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents><physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <support> Text block comprised of sized and polished, medium-weight, heavily flocked, cross-grained, straw-coloured <material>paper</material>, cross-grain, possibly handmade in <country
                           cert="medium" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/135375457">India</country>, with another comparatively thin stock added to restore folios <locus from="1" to="7">1 to 7</locus> and <locus from="218" to="222">218 to 222</locus>.</support>
                        <extent>
                           <measure unit="folios" quantity="249">249 folios (ff. ii + 249 + ii)</measure>
                           <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>308</height>
                              <width>209</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                              <height>266</height>
                              <width>143</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation xml:id="original">
                           <p>Foliation marked at top-right corners of the a sides in Hindu-Arabic numerals in black ink.</p>
                        </foliation>
                        <collation>Undetermined. Primarily quaternions throughout. 
                           <catchwords>Catchwords written written on the lower-left corners on the b sides
                              throughout.</catchwords></collation>
                        <condition>Handle with caution. In fair condition, with stains, insect damage, historical repairs, and corrosive verdigris marginal ruling throughout the original portion of hte volume.</condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" ruledLines="27" n="mistara">Written in 1 column,
                           with 27 lines per page. Ruled with a <hi rend="italic">misṭarah</hi> hand guide.</layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="nastaliq" medium="ink">Written in a clear, small nastaliq hand in <material>black</material>, with subheaders in
                        <material>red</material>.</handNote>
                                       </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote type="illumination">Illuminated header on folio <locus from="1b" to="1b">1b</locus>.</decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <lb/>
                     <label>Inscriptions:</label>
                     <list>
                        <item>The <locus from="ia" to="ia">first right flyleaf a side (f. ia)</locus> bears the title of the volume and the name of former owner <persName type="supplied" key="person_f830" role="fmo" change="#role-assignment">Colonel George William Hamilton</persName>.</item>
                        <item>
                           Folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus> bears an undated, partially obliterated nasta‘liq inscription by former owner <persName role="ins fmo">Āqā Muḥammad Kāẓim, son of Muḥammad Hādī Iṣfahānī</persName>, which he also signed twice with his <hi rend="italic">tughra</hi> (calligraphic name emblem) above and below. A <hi rend="italic">munājāt</hi> prayer in a bold nasta'liq hand trimmed off at the fore-edge.
                        </item>
                     </list>
                  </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1861" notAfter="1865">
                        <p>Probably uniformly rebound in a hybrid British-Indian style in <placeName
                           cert="high" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7002481">Multan</placeName>, together with the other volumes in full red goatskin <material>leather</material> over <material>pasteboards</material>, without a flap (type III binding per Déroche), as a set for former owner <persName type="supplied" key="person_f830" role="fmo" change="#role-assignment">Colonel George William Hamilton</persName>.</p>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                           <height>326</height>
                           <width>216</width>
                           <depth>42</depth>
                        </dimensions></p>
                        <condition>Handle with caution. In fair condition, text block split between <locus from="121b" to="124a">121b to 124a</locus>, and with the opening of other areas restricted due to cross-grain paper. Exterior abraded, tail headcap broken, and doublure separating at the tail edge of the <locus from="left_board" to="left_board">left board</locus>, and white salts (spew) likely resulting from prolonged exposure to moisture.</condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <sealDesc>
                     <seal type="stamp">
                        <decoNote type="stamp">
                           <p>A round partial seal,
                              intaglio-carved in nasta‘liq script in three stacked lines, double-ruled, impressed
                              in black ink on folio <locus from="1a" to="1a"
                                 >1a</locus>, with the name of <persName role="fmo" cert="medium">Kasht(?) Hādī</persName>, evidently a courtier of Prince Muḥammad Mu‘aẓẓam Bahādur Shāh, son of the Mughal Emperor ‘Ālamgīr I, who later succeeded him as <persName role="dte" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/314901452" key="person_314901452">Shāh ‘Ālam Bahādur I (r. 1707–1712)</persName>, dated <date
                              calendar="#Hijri-qamari" notBefore="1674-04-04" notAfter="1675-03-26">
                              1085 AH (1674–75 CE)</date> with what may be a princely regnal year of 21</p>: <p><q xml:lang="fa"> 
                                    کشت (؟) هادی مرید شاه عالم[۲۱] ،١۰۸۵</q></p>
                           <p><dimensions type="stamp" unit="mm">
                              <height>28</height>
                              <width>28</width>
                           </dimensions></p>
                         </decoNote>
                     </seal>
                  </sealDesc>
                  <accMat>Four folios (two bifolia) loosely inserted at the front of the volume bear a table of contents written in a hand consistent with many other volumes that Hamilton formerly owned.</accMat>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin><origPlace cert="medium">Probably <country
                     cert="medium" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208">India</country></origPlace><origDate cert="medium" calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1700" notAfter="1800"> undated, but possibly 18th century.</origDate> 
                     Originally completed together with <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6890"><idno>Persian MS 393</idno></ref>.</origin>
                  <provenance><p>Formerly owned by one <persName role="ins fmo">Āqā Muḥammad Kāẓim, son of Muḥammad Hādī Iṣfahānī</persName>, as per his inscription and signatures on folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Subsequently obtained by <persName type="supplied" key="person_f830"
                     role="fmo" change="#role-assignment">Colonel George William Hamilton
                     (1807-1868)</persName> who served in <country ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208">India</country>
                     <date calendar="#Gregorian" from="1823" to="1867">from 1823 to 1867</date>,
                     latterly as Commissioner in <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001535">Delhi</placeName>. During his tenure, he acquired over a
                     thousand Indian and Persian manuscripts, from which the <orgName type="corporation" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/134857252"
                        >British Museum</orgName> selected 352 volumes after his death, now held in the <orgName
                           type="corporation" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/121814978">British
                           Library</orgName>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>In <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                     when="1868">1868</date>, <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/" key="person_97751058"> Alexander
                        Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford (1812–1880)</persName> purchased the remainder.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName type="standard" role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                     >Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                        when="1901">1901</date> from <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420"
                           change="#role-assignment">James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford
                           (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName type="standard" key="person_f6379">Enriqueta
                        Rylands</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908">1908</date>
                        to the <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands
                           Library</orgName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
